The data consists of 12 variables of components, properties, alcohol

content, and quality of 1599 red wines. I will look at which properties

correlate with the wine being considered a higher quality. The quality scale

is probably 1-10 but the data only has a range of 3-8 so well consider 8

a best case scenario.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

I chose the pH histogram because I was really surprised to find that most

wine is between 3.2 and 3.5 pH. Compared to coffees average of around 5,

thats very acidic. The popularity of alkaline water and wine right now

among hipsters is a strange contrast.

Plot Two

Plot 2 is another one that surprised me. Sulphates in wine are a result of

pesticides being sprayed on grapes. I get that grapes are a fragile fruit

and pesticides keep whole crops from being destroyed, but I really didnt

expect their presence to enhance quality.

Plot Three

## Warning: Removed 166 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

Plot 3 was chosen because I really expected more sugar to correlate to a

wine being higher quality since what makes grapes tasty is thier sweetness.

I was surprised to see a basically flat line when compared to quality. Even

after zooming in on the box plots by cutting off some outliers, the drop off

in sugar for the highest quality wines ruins the positive correlation.

Reflection

Wine has been credited for various healthy properties like being high in resveratrol and other antioxidants. Considering the acidity though, itll likely wreck your teeth. My cooking experience had me expecting salt, sweet, and acid to be what makes it taste good. Im not convinced by these results that Quality is related it tasting good since higher sulphates correlated with quality. Also, salt usually makes things taste better even when their supposed to be sweet, but here we find that salt had a negative correlation with quality.
